        ],
        "date": "2026-07-15",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-15T14:52:34.763Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz remains effectively closed, with PortWatch's most recent published day (2026-07-12) recording only 10 transits against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day. Scraper-derived 24-hour arrivals at Gulf ports reached 415 vessels, a figure reflecting a different and broader methodology than PortWatch's chokepoint count and not directly comparable to it. The Hormuz Index state composite sits at 91 (extreme), unchanged over the past 24 hours, with physical transit deviation remaining its top contributor. The 30-day escalation forecast composite stands separately at 65 (high), also unchanged, driven primarily by Polymarket closure-odds positioning; the divergence between the two readings reflects a market that sees conditions as already catastrophic but is not yet pricing a near-term step-change in severity. On the kinetic front, Iranian state media (IRNA and Mehr News) claims the IRGC struck U.S. military facilities in Jordan and Kuwait during Operation Nasr-2, while senior naval officials framed a strike on the Dena destroyer as evidence of adversary weakness. Per gCaptain, President Trump pledged to intensify bombardment until Iran reopens the waterway. Tehran has simultaneously threatened closure of the Bab al-Mandab Strait. Brent's 1.83% decline to $84.24 suggests oil markets are weighing demand-side risk as heavily as any supply premium, a notable signal given the scale of reported interdiction activity.",
